# Weekly Work Reports (Manager-ready)

When the user asks for a **work report**, **weekly report**, **progress report**, or similar for their manager/CEO:

## How to produce it

1. Base content on **git commits** for the requested date range (`git log --since=… --until=…`) plus recent conversation work if relevant.
2. Prefer **English**, professional, manager-friendly tone (same style as prior reports for this project).
3. Save under `reports/` as markdown when useful, e.g. `reports/work-report-YYYY-MM-DD-to-YYYY-MM-DD.md`.
4. If they ask for multiple reports (e.g. 3 weeks), split by week (Mon–Fri) and explain each week separately.

## Required style — explain everything

Do **not** dump raw commit messages. For each item:

- Say **what** was done in plain language
- Briefly say **why it matters** (business/UX value) where helpful
- Group by **day** or clear themes (Hero, About, Contracts, Blog, etc.)
- Include a short **Week Summary** at the top and an **Outcomes for Management** table or bullets at the bottom

## Structure template

```markdown
# Weekly Work Report
**Project:** vCloudTech Marketing Website
**Period:** [dates]
**Prepared by:** Usama Khan
**For:** Manager / Leadership Review

## Week Summary
[2–4 sentences]

## [Day], [Date]
### [Theme]
- What was done…
- Why it matters (when useful)…

## Outcomes for Management
| Area | Outcome |
|------|---------|

## Notes
[Optional carry-over / next focus]
```

## Quality bar

- Clearer and more polished than a commit log — “better more” each time if possible
- Honest: only claim work backed by commits or verified conversation work
- Keep day-by-day explanation readable for someone who did not watch the coding session
